or provocateurs, played key roles in shaping the conflict, and the conflict equally impacted the course of literary history. The volume shows how a wide variety of genres and works are deeply engaged with responses to the war, from women's visionary writing by figures like Catherine of Siena to anonymous lyric poetry, from Christine de Pizan's Book of the City of Ladies to Geoffrey Chaucer's Canterbury Tales.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aHundred Years' War, 1339-1453. 0aLiterature, Medieval. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh1 aBrown, Jennifer N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aButterfield, Ardis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavies, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavies, Daniel, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aElst, Stefan Vander, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFulton, Helen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGalloway, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGiancarlo, Matthew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHicks-Bartlett, Alani, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMattison, J. R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPerry, R. D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPerry, R. D., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aStaley, Lynn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStrakhov, Elizaveta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary